Mercy Mwai @wangumarci Ten members of the National Assembly now want a lifestyle audit conducted on Deputy President William Ruto to determine his wealth as they defended the Central Organisation of Trade Unions (Cotu) secretary general Francis Atwoli’s recent remarks. Addressing a news conference yesterday at Parliament Buildings, the legislators claimed it would be in the interest of Ruto if the country knows his total income as this would  clear the air on what exactly he owns. Deserve respect “A lifestyle audit should be carried out on the DP based on his known income,”reads a statement from the MPs. The MPs who included Ayub Savula (Lugari), Beatrice Adagala (Vihiga county), Alfred Agoi (Sabatia), Simba Arati (Dagoretti North), Kassait Kamket (Tiaty), Tom Kajwang (Ruaraka), Sakwa Bunyasi (Nambale), Raphael Wanjala (Budalangi) told off  those attacking Atwoli saying he deserves respect from all Kenyans. Led by Savula, the MPs claimed Atwoli made the remarks that Ruto will not be on the ballot come 2022 due to his alleged disrespect for President Uhuru Kenyatta, especially on the war against corruption.